        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> This happened when I was trying to port my existing `vim.pack` setup to a new machine. Admittedly I did have some errors in my configuration, but I definitely did not make any manual modifications.\r\n\r\nI am pretty sure that this would not have happened without some out-of-scope action with the lockfile. Its contents are [repaired](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/11084f5db38267f23f5aa2abb784d56c0c6d310e/runtime/lua/vim/pack.lua#L847) [during the first `vim.pack.add()` call](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/11084f5db38267f23f5aa2abb784d56c0c6d310e/runtime/lua/vim/pack.lua#L935-L938).\r\n\r\nThe expected workflow if there is a missing `rev` field in the lockfile is:\r\n- Run `vim.pack.update()` and see errors.\r\n- Run `:checkhealth vim.pack`. It [will show](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/11084f5db38267f23f5aa2abb784d56c0c6d310e/runtime/lua/vim/pack/health.lua#L95-L98) something like `❌ ERROR \"plugin-name\" `rev` entry is missing. Delete \"plugin-name\" entry (do not create trailing comma) and restart Nvim to regenerate lockfile data`. The suggestion is a bit general, but it will work here. In case of missing `rev` it will also work to just restart.\r\n- Follow the steps in `:checkhealth vim.pack` and repair the lockfile.\r\n\r\nI think adding extra safeguards here is not necessary as it duplicates the `:checkhealth` logic and should not happen often (there must be a lockfile edit *after* starting a current Nvim session).",
